text: A variety of socioeconomic and cultural factors were identified as major barriers to accessing and utilizing MHCS. Over half of the women surveyed cited poverty, illiteracy, restrictions from their husbands, the distance to health facilities, and long queues as reasons for not using services. Additionally, over a third of the women pointed to cultural practices within their communities as a cause for delays in seeking care. These findings reveal that addressing maternal health in this region requires more than just improving clinical services; it also means tackling deeply rooted societal and personal challenges that women face daily.
translated: [Setšoantšo sa tša ekonomi le setšoantšo sa bodumedi sa hlomphegilego sa bontšhitšwe bjalo ka ditšhweletšo tše kgolo go fihlela le go šomiša MHCS. Ka moka ga basadi ba babedi ba baopilwe ba hlahlobe tlala, go se na bokgoni bja go bala, dikgobalo tša bona ba bašwago, pego ya ditoropong tša tšhireletšo ya maphelo le dibjalo tše telele bjalo ka diteko tša go se šome mahala. Gape, ka moka ga basadi ba babedi ba baopilwe ba bontšhitše tša setšoantšo sa bodumedi ka gare ga maphelo a bona bjalo ka sabo sa go kgotha go fihlela ka go kwa tšhireletšo. Diteko tše di bontšhitše gore go rarolla bophelo bja basadi ba bašwago mo gole gona go hloka go fokotša tšhireletšo ya mahala; gape go rialo go lwantšha ditšhweletšo tša setšoantšo le tša motho ka moka tšeo basadi ba di hlatšago ka letšatši le letšatši.]
backtranslated: [Economic status and respectable religious image were cited as the main motivations for achieving and using MHCS. Both of these women were asked to assess hunger, illiteracy, their own personal injuries, urban health insurance record and high crops as unemployment tests. Also, both of these women were asked to show religious status in their lives as a motivation to achieve a sense of security. These tests showed that addressing the lives of these women in the upbringing does not reduce the need for free security; it also counters the image and human prejudices that women report on a daily basis.]

text: Despite his shortcomings, Unoka was a talented musician. He was a tall but very thin man with a slight stoop and a mournful look, which would disappear when he was drinking or playing his flute. His happiest moments came in the months after the harvest, when the village musicians would retrieve their instruments from above the fireplace. Unoka would join them, his face filled with pure joy and peace. Sometimes, other villages would invite Unoka and his band to teach them their tunes, and they would stay for several months, sharing their music.

text: At the Derby Avenue RC Basic School and St. George’s Anglican Basic School in Accra, invigilators were captured openly demanding GH¢60 daily tokens, supervisors pocketed envelopes of GH¢400, and candidates were asked to contribute to an Aseda Offertory. John Kapi stressed that once WAEC provides feedback on such incidents, it is the responsibility of the Ghana Education Service (GES) to take decisive action. And so when these issues come up, once the feedback goes to them, we [WAEC] expect that they would react appropriately and ensure that the right action is taken against the people, he said.
translated: [Go Derby Avenue RC Basic School le St. George’s Anglican Basic School kua Accra, ba invigilators ba ile ba tshwara ba kopa GH¢60 ya ditekene tša letsatsi, ba supervisor ba ile ba tšwara dipitsa tša GH¢400, le ba kandidati ba ile ba kopa gore ba etse Aseda Offertory. Le ge mabaka ao a tšwa, ge feedback e ya go bona, re [WAEC] re tšwenyega gore ba tla reagisa ka tsela e swanago le gore ba tla dira tšwanelo go ba ba ba tshwenyegago, a re.]
backtranslated: [At Derby Avenue RC Basic School and St. George's Anglican Basic School in Accra, the invigilators held up and demanded GH¢60 for solar tickets, the supervisors held up pots for GH¢400, and the candidates asked to imitate the Aseda Offertory. text: For rural communities in Ghana, especially in the Kumbungu district, access to and use of maternal healthcare services (MHCS) remain a significant challenge. This study set out to explore the specific barriers preventing women from utilizing these services and to evaluate the quality of care provided. The research adopted a mixed-methods approach, combining both quantitative and qualitative data to get a comprehensive view of the situation. This phased design involved surveying 441 pregnant and postpartum women and conducting interviews with 20 healthcare providers. A facility checklist was also used to assess the state of clinics, including the availability of essential drugs and equipment.

text: Okonkwo was a man of great renown throughout his nine villages and even beyond, a fame built entirely on his own remarkable achievements. At just eighteen years old, he brought honor to his village by defeating Amalinze the Cat, a legendary wrestler who had been undefeated for seven years. Amalinze earned his nickname because his back never once touched the earth. The old men of the village considered Okonkwo's victory one of the fiercest fights they had ever seen.
translated: [Okonkwo e ne le motho wa kgosi gohle kwa ditoropong tše dingwe tša gagwe le go feta, kgosi e eketwang ka ditsheo tša gagwe tša kgonthe. A bile a na maswabi a lesome mabedi, o ile a kgontha kgosi ya motse wa gagwe ka go fenya Amalinze ya kgosi, mokgathi wa kgosi o a neng a sa fenwe ke motho go fihla ka dingwaga tše tshelela. Amalinze o ile a kgona leina la gagwe ka baka la gore sefahle sa gagwe se ne se sa kgona go tshela lefatshe. Basaudi ba motse ba ile ba kgontha kgosi ya Okonkwo e le ya ditsheo tše di kgonthang tše ba di bonele.]
backtranslated: [Okonkwo was the king's man everywhere in his other towns and more, a king betrayed by his real choices. And with twelve regrets, he won the king of his town by defeating the king's Amalinze, the king's concubine who was undefeated for six years. Amalinze won his name because his face could cross the earth. The townspeople won the king of Okonkwo as the king of the optical choices.]

text: The study also shed light on significant facility-based challenges that compromise the quality of care. A key issue was the inadequate number of midwives, which likely contributes to the long queues women reported. Additionally, the absence of essential equipment and drugs was a major problem. For example, health service providers specifically recommended a greater number of trained midwives and the provision of critical logistics like ultrasound machines and proper delivery equipment to ensure effective and high-quality care.

text: Okonkwo was an imposing figure, tall and massive with a severe expression, a result of his bushy eyebrows and wide nose. His breathing was so heavy that his family could hear it from their own houses when he slept. When he walked, his heels barely touched the ground, making him seem poised to pounce on someone—which he often did. He had a slight stammer, and in moments of anger, he would resort to his fists when words failed him. He had no patience for men who were not successful, and this sentiment stemmed from his deep-seated shame for his own father.

text: The study found that while a high percentage of women did engage with some maternal health services—87.5% attended antenatal care (ANC), 87.3% had a skilled delivery, and 84.8% had a postnatal care (PNC) visit—the frequency of care was a concern. A little over half of the participants (53.4%) had the recommended four or more ANC visits, and nearly half (46.9%) didn't register until their second trimester. These figures highlight a gap between initial access and consistent, timely utilization of services, suggesting that women may be facing obstacles that prevent them from fully engaging with the healthcare system throughout their pregnancies.

text: The crowd held its breath as the drums beat and the flutes sang. Amalinze was a clever opponent, but Okonkwo was just as skilled, and as slippery as a fish in water. Both men were incredibly strong, their muscles and nerves straining to the point of almost breaking. But in the end, Okonkwo emerged victorious. This monumental win was just the beginning of his legacy. Over the next twenty years, his fame spread like a wildfire, fueled by his unwavering resolve and personal triumphs.
translated: [Thobela e ile ya tšwela moya ya yona ge di-pa le ge di-pela. Amalinze e be e le mmueledi wa kgale, empa Okonkwo e be e le mmueledi wa kgale, e bile e le e lebala kama madi a a tšwelago mo go lebale. Batho ba babedi ba be ba lebala kudu, madi a bona le dintho tša bona di be di tšwelago go fihla kwa go fela. Hela, Okonkwo a tšwela pele a feditše. Kgetho ye e kgolo e be e le thobela ya go qala ga kgale ya gagwe. Ka mafelo a masome a mabedi a nywaga, kgale ya gagwe e ile ya tšwelago kama mollo wa mose, o o tšwelago ka kgale ya gagwe le diphetho tša gagwe tša motho.]
backtranslated: [The audience went out of their minds as the pa and the pela. Amalinze was an old lawyer, but Okonkwo was an old lawyer, and a forgetful kama blood that went out of the memory. The two people were very forgetful, their blood and their wounds went out to the end. Hela, Okonkwo went on to finish. This great choice was the beginning of the end of his old. By the end of the twenties, his old continued kama the fire of the old, which went out of his old and his personal decisions.]

text: To improve maternal health in the Kumbungu district, both study participants and service providers offered actionable recommendations. Women suggested focusing on public education about maternal care, enforcing free MHCS, and improving the local road network to make facilities more accessible. Providers emphasized the need for more midwives and better equipment. The study concludes that both governmental and non-governmental organizations must increase investment in maternal health and address the broader socioeconomic issues affecting women. This comprehensive approach, tackling both healthcare system deficiencies and community-level barriers, is essential for truly improving maternal health outcomes.
translated: [Go fokotsa bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng mo ditshepeng tsa Kumbungu, batho ba ba ithutelweng le badiri ba tshireletso ba ne ba kgetha maikemisetso a a kgonegago. Basadi ba be ba kopa gore go rulagane le thuto ya kgwele ya bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng, go tshegetsa gore tshireletso ya bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng e se e kgonegago, le go fokotsa tsela ya kgwele gore tshireletso di kgonegago. Badiri ba tshireletso ba be ba kopa gore go na le badiri ba bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng ba bantši le tshireletso e e kgonegago. Thuto e e kwala gore mafapha a setšhaba le a setšhabeng a swanetše go fokotsa kgwele ya tshireletso ya bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng le go tshegetsa ditšhego tša kgwele tša setšhaba tša basadi. Tsela e e kgonegago, e e tshegetswago ke tshireletso ya bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng le ditšhego tša kgwele tša setšhaba, e kgonega go fokotsa bophelo bja basadi ba baetsweng.]
backtranslated: [To reduce the life of women born in Kumbungu camps, the study population and safety personnel selected feasible targets. The women requested that a women's health league study be organized, supporting that women's health league is not feasible, and reducing the course of the league so that safety personnel are feasible. The safety personnel requested that there be more women's health leagues with feasible safety personnel. The study concluded that the public and community sectors should reduce the women's health league and support national women's health leagues. A feasible course, supported by women's health league and community safety teams, is feasible to reduce the women's health league.]

text: Unoka, Okonkwo's father, had passed away ten years prior. He was a man known for his laziness and carelessness, living only for the present with no thought for the future. Any money he managed to acquire—which was a rare occurrence—he would immediately spend on palm-wine, gathering his neighbors for a celebration. He believed that to see a dead man's mouth was to see the foolishness of not eating what you had in life. Unoka was also deeply in debt, owing money to nearly every one of his neighbors.
